:::summary
Latin is the classical language of ancient Rome and one of the most influential languages ever spoken. It is the ancestor of the modern Romance languages — Spanish, French, Italian, Portuguese, and Romanian — and has contributed more vocabulary to English than any other foreign language. Latin was the language of the early Christian church, Western scholarship for over a millennium, and remains a living language in Catholic liturgy and scholarly tradition.
:::

